{
  "doc_id": "24222",
  "text": "The dysregulation of p53 via E6 during vegetative amplification is also necessary to provide an environment conducive for viral DNA amplification. Viruses that are unable to degrade or inactivate p53 are unable to amplify viral DNA in a stratified epithelium [CITATION_1] . Separate from its role in checkpoint control, p53 can directly inhibit amplification replication in several PVs [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , perhaps by directly binding to the E2 protein [CITATION_5] . Therefore, like other viruses, HPVs take advantage of some aspects of the DDR, but inactivate others.",
